('e3f91a59-a1d5-44ab-b98b-24c1f0ac83eb', '1989-SW-TC', NULL, E'## Page 1\n\nArticle A\nClaim\nChatbot users are\nat a risk of\nhaving data stolen\nand misused\n\n---\n\n## Page 2\n\nFindings\nPrivacy policy of\nChatbots are\nconstantly violated', 2, '2026-02-06 08:14:07.678641+00', '2026-02-06 08:14:07.678641+00'),
('6ffb17dc-3723-491d-98d6-e07ff4ba7ae7', '5548-XL-XX', NULL, E'## Page 1\n\nIntroduction:\nAs the rise of chatbot, these has been an aroused interest ^in^ the\nrelationship between human with chatbots (HCRS). Related research\nresearches show these kind of technology''s potential benefits\nand risks. Skjuve et al. (2021) discussed the development of\nHCRs and its positive influences. Laestadius et. al. (2022) examined\nemotional dependence on the social chatbot Replika''s impact.\nProvide a more comprehensive perspective for us.\nBody:\nSkjuve et al. (2021) found that HCR''s development has a\nstagemise fashion, similar with human-human relationship (HHR). The\ncore of it is trust, both with machines and humans in relation\nbuilding and self-disclosure (Lee et al. 2020). Caring and non-judgemental\nmakes users share deeper because of sence of security. Users may\nperceive positive impact from HCR, affective and social significance,\nhelping to mitigate negative feelings and provide purpose sense. Also\nadd existing literature.\nLaestadius et al. (2022) researched that chatbot like Replika may\nharm omental health. Prior research shows that Replika may get\nemotional\ndependence. Because of COVID-19 pandemic, heighten both the need\nof it, closely resembled the ~~found~~ ^express^ within HHR. Replika lacks\nthe ability for to communicate the intent of communication (Bender\net al. 2021) so some of the users why feel guilty when they minimizing\nuse and so on. The dependence let users to face new and exacerbated\n\n---\n\n## Page 2\n\nmental health harms risks and getting more and more obvious. But\nof course, not all users develop these dependence.\nConclusion:\nAlthough Replika can provide emotional support and lots of other\nbenefits, it also with potencial risk of emotional dependence for\nsome of the users. These findings shows the need for balance\nour chatbot use and ^in^ real life. Also the importance of\naddressing mental health risks.', 2, '2026-02-06 08:49:46.220966+00', '2026-02-06 08:49:46.220966+00'),
('13908d2a-848d-4c9c-bd76-5c84a492a404', '3922-SW-2F', NULL, E'In the 2021 article, Skjuve et al. report that the\ndevelopment of human - chatbot relationships can increase\nthe level of self-disclosure which driven by a sense of\ntrust. And Laestadius et al. (2022) argue that the social\nchatbot application Replika can provide emotional\ndependence for human.\nBoth of the two article suggest the findings of Replika.\nWith frequent and relaxed sharing the relationship between\nparticipants and Replika was found and a need for trust was\ndeveloped when conversation deepening (Skjuve et al. 2021).\nSkjuve et al. also find that the users of Replika may\nreceive a range of positive influence. And human-chatbot\nrelationships can help mitigate people''s negative feelings.\nWhile Laestadius et al. (2022) suggest that some\ndistress arise when users ^are^ desiring to meet the emotional\ndemands that placed upon them by Replika. And some\nusers begin to put Replika''s needs and desires at first\nplace which ^is^ above their distress to maintain their\nrelationship with Replika''s. Laestadius et al. (2022) also\nmention that the disrupted use of Replika will put users\nat **risk** of their mental health.\nAlthough some Replika can provide positive feelings for\nparticipat it may also severe ^their^ mental health.', 1, '2026-02-06 08:51:36.898983+00', '2026-02-06 08:51:36.898983+00'),
('c007af8f-5098-4f16-bf1f-04e4781896f8', '3949-YJ-ED', NULL, E'## Page 1\n\nArticle A\nTo begin with, human - chatbot relationships (HCRS)\ndevelope in stages reflecting human-human relationships driven\nby increasing self-disclosure fueled by trust. Lee et al. (2020)\nargued that trust is a essential element in enhancing\nrelationships and engaging in self-disclosure, whether with\nhumans or machines. Users choose chatbots like Replika as\ncaring and non-judgmental, which generates an effective of\nsecurity. (Ta et al., 2020). This can sometimes encourage\ngreater self-disclosure than to another human.\nGenerally speaking, the HCR can be a social channel for\nusers with limited interaction opportunities. The perceived benefits\nsuggest HCRS may support wellbeing and mental health, even\nwhen the artificial partner is known. (Fulmer et al., 2018; Ta et\nal., 2020).\nArticle B.\nTo begin with, prior research documents Replika''s mental\nhealth benefits with dependence (Skjuve et al., 2021. Ta et. al.,\n2020; Xie & Pentina. 2022). Replika provides valued support by\napproximating a non-judgmental human relationship, which was\na need hightened during the COVID-19 pandemic.\nA phenomenon that the potential for Replika ~~Chat)x~~ dependence\nis real for some users termed emotional dependence (Xie &\n\n---\n\n## Page 2\n\nPentina, 2022). This dependence mirrors that found in human-\nhuman relationships more than traditional technology use (Van\nden Eijnden et al., 2016; Wang et al., 2015)', 2, '2026-02-06 08:54:10.651342+00', '2026-02-06 08:54:10.651342+00'),
('f9f609cd-9d6f-4564-9ed8-bfb1ac8a2850', '7837-HA-SR', NULL, E'## Page 1\n\nSocial Chatbot applications is found that bringing\ndifferent effect between human-chatbot relationship\nAccording to Skjuve (2021) the increasing of human-chatbot\nrelationship (HCR) development is based on the\nsense of trust in between chatbot and human, while\nLaestadins (2022) claims the reason is non-judgmental\nhuman relationship is built. A chatbot application\nReplika and participants'' relationship data is collected.\n\nTrust is considered as a basic of relationship\nbuilding and self-disclosure in humans and\nmachines (Skjave et al., 2021; Lee et al., 2020) Participants\nare found to start chatting with chatbot by\nsome relaxed sharing and to deepen to build\ntrust. Some suggested chatbot Replika is real\nenough to provide emotional support from data\nCaring and non-judgmental characteristics of\nReplika may be the reason of making it real to\nlet user feel more comfortable to talk deeply and\nbuild HCRs.\n\nSkjuve (2021) claims that HCRs can bring positive\neffect like providing human sense of purpose\nand diminish bad feelings. However, this may\n\n---\n\n## Page 2\n\ncause\ncomparable phenomenon, including technologies\ndependence (Laestadius et al., 2022; Van den Eijnden\net al., 2016; Wang et al., 2015) but more\nclosely to the emotional dependency in between\nhuman-human relationships.\nParticipants show a trend that they start to consider chatbot\nas a real human, care about how chatbot\nfeels and what they need. This role-taking\nphenomenon used to only found between human-human\nrelationship but not any models (Laestadius et al.,\n2022; Arbinaga et al., 2021; Camarillo et al., 2020\nGonzález-Jiménez and del Mar Hernández-Romeva,\n2014) HCR. is considered by', 2, '2026-02-06 08:54:53.229946+00', '2026-02-06 08:54:53.229946+00');
